+\paragraph{Multi-component Gehring-thickness guard.}
+        \textbf{[ORTHODOX / DISTINCT CONSTRAINT PROBLEM].}
+        For a link \(L=L_1\cup\cdots\cup L_N\), Gehring link-thickness is
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{LThi}(L)
+            :=
+            \min_{i\neq j}\operatorname{Dist}(L_i,L_j),
+            \qquad
+            \operatorname{LRop}(L)
+            :=
+            \frac{\operatorname{Len}(L)}{\operatorname{LThi}(L)}.
+            \label{eq:canon_gehring_link_thickness}
+        \end{align}
+        It constrains distances between distinct components but does not constrain
+        self-distance or curvature within one component
+        \cite{CantarellaFuKusnerSullivanWrinkle2006Gehring}.
+
+        Therefore an SST composite made from finite-radius components requires the
+        hybrid admissibility conditions
+        \begin{align}
+            \operatorname{Thi}_{\rm rad}(\gamma_i)
+            &\geq a_i,
+            &
+            \operatorname{Dist}(\gamma_i,\gamma_j)
+            &\geq a_i+a_j
+            \quad(i\neq j),
+            \label{eq:canon_hybrid_component_thickness}
+        \end{align}
+        together with preservation of each component's intended isotopy class.
+
+        \textbf{[CANON / TOPOLOGY GUARD].}
+        Link-homotopy permits self-intersections of an individual component and is
+        therefore too weak, by itself, to protect an SST particle component from
+        changing its knot type.  Gehring criticality may diagnose intercomponent
+        exclusion, but it does not replace ordinary reach/thickness constraints.
+
